 F3 - READ a pager
      This section allows you to read a pager and display its configuration.
      You may change any of the options, then choose to program a pager, save
      the configuration to disk, or print the configuration.

 F5 - PROGRAM a single pager
      This section allows you to select the options you want in your pager.
      You may then choose to program a pager, save the configuration to disk,
      or print the configuration.

                                                  <Page Down>    <Page Up> 
.p

 F6 - PROGRAM sequential pagers
      This section allows you to select the options you want for a group of
      pagers. The Inventory Control Number and Pager Codes which you enter*
      will automatically be incremented each time through the programming
      sequence. As in programming single pagers, you may change any of the
      options, program a pager, save the configuration to disk or print the
      configuration. Pressing F10 or ESC at any of the menus will terminate
      the sequential programming and return you to the Main menu.

     *NOTE:  Only the codes with individual code types will be incremented.


                                                  <Page Down>    <Page Up> 
.p

 F8 - RETRIEVE a stored pager configuration from disk
      This section allows you to retrieve one of the pager configurations
      which you have saved to disk. The Inventory Control Number may be an
      actual inventory control number of a pager or it may be a name of a 
      template file used to identify one of the common types of pagers you
      program.

                                                  <Page Down>    <Page Up> 
.p

 F9 - SETUP computer configuration
      This section allows you to setup your computer configuration. You
      can select the disk drive and path name in which your configuration
      files are archived, the disk drive and path name in which the HELP
      files are stored and the communications port that is used to
      communicate to the Radio Interface Box.
